      <title>Dutch container search stumbles on shipwreck</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANDutch salvage teams looking for shipping containers that fell off a ship during a storm discovered a 16th Century shipwreck on the North Sea floor, according to the BBC. The ancient wreck was found during a search for missing cargo that fell from the ship MSC Zoe during a January 2 storm in the North Sea, when 345 containers fell off the vessel. According to the BBC, as salvage teams searched the Dutch North Sea, their sonar equipment discovered an unknown object on the seafloor a few miles to the north of Terschelling Island in the Wadden Sea. The salvage teams recovered some copper cargo, three wooden planks and 12 wooden ribs from the ship's frame. According to the BBC, experts believe the 30 meter by 7 meter ship could have been transporting as much as 5,000 kilograms of copper. According to a statement by the country's science and culture ministry, "it's the oldest sea-going ship ever found in Dutch waters.""An immediate archaeological survey was started and researchers determined the wood dated from 1536," the ministry said. It also added that the ship was built around 1540 during the reign of Charles V. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of shipwreck and MSC Zoe2. Salvage ship discovering shipwreck3. Things recovered from shipwreck and ship dimensions4. Shipwreck thought to have been built in 1540VOICEOVER (in English): "Dutch salvage teams looking for shipping containers that fell off a ship during a storm discovered a 16th Century shipwreck on the North Sea floor." "The ancient wreck was found during a search for missing cargo that fell from the ship MSC Zoe during a January 2 storm in the North Sea, when 345 containers fell off the vessel." "According to the BBC, as salvage teams searched the Dutch North Sea, their sonar equipment discovered an unknown object on the seafloor a few miles to the north of Terschelling Island in the Wadden Sea." "The salvage teams recovered some copper cargo, three wooden planks and 12 wooden ribs from the ship's frame." "According to the BBC, experts believe the 30 meter by 7 meter ship could have been transporting as much as 5,000 kilograms of copper." "The country's science and culture ministry said in a statement that "it's the oldest sea-going ship ever found in Dutch waters.""According to the ministry, "an immediate archaeological survey was started and researchers determined the wood dated from 1536.""It also added that the ship was built around 1540 during the reign of Charles V." SOURCES: BBC, Channel News Asiahttps://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-47799292https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/dutch-container-search-reveals-rare-ancient-shipwreck--11409990***]]></description>
