      <title>Israeli spacecraft attempts to land on the moon</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANAn Israeli space probe, called the Beresheet, entered lunar orbit last week and is set to land on the moon's surface on Thursday, The Times of Israel reports.The spacecraft performed a maneuver to reduce its distance from the moon from 750 kilometers to 467 kilometers.According to Space.com, the probe will land on the Mare Serenitatis, which is on the northern hemisphere of the near side region of the moon. The spacecraft will focus on three possible landing sites in the area. These are  Posidonius 1, 2 or 3.Once the probe lands, it will use a magnetometer to measure the magnetism of moon rocks, according to an Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs news release This is to get a better understanding of how and when the lunar body acquired its magnetic field. If successful, Israel will become the fourth country to land a probe on the moon. Previously, nations such as the former Soviet Union, the United States and China have landed a spacecraft on the moon. The mission is a joint project between private Israeli company SpaceIL and Israel Aerospace Industries.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The spacecraft and the moon2. The spacecraft approaching the moon3. Possible landing sites and the spacecraft landing on the moon4. The spacecraft on the moon and moon rocksVOICEOVER (in English): "The Times of Israel reports that an Israeli space probe, called the Beresheet, entered lunar orbit last week and is set to land on the moon's surface on Thursday.""The spacecraft performed a maneuver to reduce its distance from the moon from 750 kilometers to 467 kilometers.""According to Space.com, the probe will land on the Mare Serenitatis, which is on the northern hemisphere of the near side region of the moon.""The spacecraft will focus on three possible landing sites in the area. Therese are:  Posidonius 1, 2 or 3.""According to an Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs news release, once the probe lands, it will use a magnetometer to measure the magnetism of moon rocks.""This is to get a better understanding of how and when the lunar body acquired its magnetic field."SOURCES: Forbes, NBC News, Israel Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Space.com, The Jerusalem Post, Haaretz, Space IL,    https://www.forbes.com/sites/gregautry/2019/04/08/the-future-begins-on-thursday-beresheet-moonlander-leads-an-israeli-new-space-wave/#416527b04ff3https://www.nbcnews.com/mach/science/israel-s-beresheet-space-probe-prepares-historic-moon-landing-ncna992671https://mfa.gov.il/MFA/InnovativeIsrael/ScienceTech/Pages/Beresheet-lunar-landing-site-revealed-3-April-2019.aspxhttps://www.space.com/israel-moon-lander-lunar-touchdown-final-approach.htmlhttps://www.jpost.com/Israel-News/Capturing-the-moon-Beresheet-gears-up-to-escape-Earths-gravity-585656https://www.haaretz.com/science-and-health/.premium-next-stop-the-moon-israeli-lunar-spacecraft-pulls-off-key-maneuver-1.7087693http://www.spaceil.com/mission/***]]></description>
