      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANWashington state lawmakers have passed a bill to allow human composting, according to CNN.If Governor Jay Inslee decides to sign Senate Bill 5001 into law, it is to take effect on May 1, 2020.Recomposition is the process of turning bodies of deceased humans into soil.Katrina Spade, the CEO of Recompse, a company that wants to build a human composting facility, explained the process to KIRO 7. She said the body is covered in natural materials such as straw or wood chips. Microbes then break down the body into the soil over a period of three to seven weeks.Relatives can then choose to keep the soil in urns, use it to plant trees or spread it on public land in Washington state, according to the Associated Press.CNN quotes the bill's sponsor Senator Jamie Pederson as saying that, "People should have the freedom to determine for themselves how they'd like their body to be disposed of..."RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Senate building, bill and depiction of human composting2. A deceased human being and soil 3. The process of how a human body is broken down into the soil4.  What relatives of the deceased human beings can choose to do with the soilVOICEOVER (in English): "According to CNN, Washington state lawmakers have passed a bill to allow human composting.""Recomposition is the process of turning bodies of deceased humans into soil.""Katrina Spade, the CEO of Recompse, a company that wants to build a human composting facility, explained the process to KIRO 7." "She said the body is covered in natural materials such as straw or wood chips. Microbes then break down the body into the soil over a period of three to seven weeks.""According to the Associated Press, relatives can then choose to keep the soil in urns, use it to plant trees or spread it on public land in Washington state."SOURCES: CNN, Seattle TImes, The Associated Press, KIRO-TVhttps://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/20/us/washington-composting-dead-bodies/index.htmlhttps://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/washington-on-the-cusp-of-becoming-first-state-to-legalize-human-composting/https://www.apnews.com/96e12b7f743b4e9c89a06155471f63c3https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/sunday-at-11-washington-on-track-to-be-first-state-to-allow-human-composting/913170404***]]></description>
